2026-06-11 | Equal Point in Bracket String

Question
Find the first equal point.
	Key Insight
Let:
		openBefore
		=
		number of '(' before current position
		closeAfter
		=
		number of ')' from current position to end
We need:
		openBefore == closeAfter
First compute total number of closing brackets.
Then scan from left to right while maintaining:
		openBefore
		closeAfter
	Approach
1.	Count total closing brackets in string.
2.	Initialize:
		openBefore = 0
		closeAfter = totalClosing
3.	Check every split position.
4.	Before processing s[i]:
		if openBefore == closeAfter
				return i
5.	Update counts:
		if s[i] == '('
				openBefore++
		else
				closeAfter--
6.	After loop, check split at n.
7.	Return n if valid.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int findEqualPoint(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        int closeAfter = 0;
        for(char ch : s) {
            if(ch == ')')
                closeAfter++;
        }
        int openBefore = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(openBefore == closeAfter)
                return i;
            if(s[i] == '(')
                openBefore++;
            else
                closeAfter--;
        }
        if(openBefore == closeAfter)
            return n;
        return -1;
    }
};
	Key Insight
At any split position k:
		left part contributes only '(' count
		right part contributes only ')' count
So by maintaining a running count of opening brackets on the left and remaining closing brackets on the right, we can find the first valid split in a single traversal.
